--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Third-party methods and datasets reproduced or referenced
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The attack catalogue reuses attacker semantics defined by prior work:

  * VeReMi and the VeReMi Extension — van der Heijden et al. (2018) and
    Kamel et al. (2020). The position and speed attacker definitions
    (constant/random position, constant/random speed, eventual stop)
    follow these references.
  * VASP (Vehicular Attack Simulation Platform) — heading, speed-offset,
    acceleration, and ghost-vehicle attacker families follow the VASP
    taxonomy.
  * F2MD / ETSI TR 103 460 — the rule-based plausibility baseline follows
    the F2MD framework (provided on request; not bundled here).

The detector zoo reimplements published detectors. Each is cited in the
paper and in the source of benchmark/detectors.py:

  * Isolation Forest (Liu et al.), Local Outlier Factor (Breunig et al.,
    2000), One-Class SVM (Schölkopf et al., 2001), Gradient Boosting,
    Deep SVDD (Ruff et al., ICML 2018), Deep Isolation Forest
    (Xu & Pang et al., TKDE 2023), Anomaly Transformer (Xu et al.,
    ICLR 2022), Graph Deviation Network (Deng & Hooi, AAAI 2021), and a
    one-layer LSTM classifier. Classical detectors use scikit-learn and
    pyod; Deep SVDD uses deepod.

Public corpora referenced in the paper (SPMD Ann Arbor, AMCD Tysons,
V2AIX Aachen, BME Budapest, and the NYC CV Pilot event data) remain under
their original licenses and are obtained from their original sources; they
are not redistributed in this repository. The Montreal corpus collected by
the authors is released separately (see the Data Availability section of
the README).
